                        <persName corresp="#p_TSM_1">Stansfield Turner</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SR_1">Sayre</persName> Stevens, Deputy Director,
                        National Foreign Assessment Center</item>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">White House</hi>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Zbigniew Brzezinski</persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d17fn2">In the right-hand margin, an unknown hand wrote
                            “(Chairman)” after <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName>’s
                            name.</note>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_UV_1">Victor Utgoff</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Robert Rosenberg</item>
                    <item>Charles Stebbins</item>
                </list>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Treaty Provisions and the Initial Approach to the
                    Soviets</p>
                <p>It was agreed that the following general provisions are acceptable as a framework
                    for future negotiations:</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">—Prohibited <hi rend="roman">(peacetime or war)</hi>
                </p>
                <p>—<gloss target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss> system testing in space or against
                    objects in space.</p>
                <p>—Use of <gloss target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss> systems or readying such systems
                    for operational use.</p>
                <pb facs="0074" n="43" xml:id="pg_43"/>
                <p>—Interference with the operation of any of the other side’s space systems,
                    including (during peacetime only) electronic warfare (EW) against satellite
                    systems.</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">—<hi rend="italic">Permitted</hi>
                </p>
                <p>—Testing of EW <gloss target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss> systems in space and
                    against space objects.<note n="3" xml:id="d17fn3">In the right-hand margin,
                            <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote “seems in conflict”
                        and drew arrows pointing to be the first sentence under the heading
                        “Prohibited” and the first sentence under “Permitted.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>—<gloss target="#t_RD_1">R&amp;D</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_ASAT_1"
                        >ASAT</gloss> testing short of space or ground-to-space testing.</p>
                <p>However, the provisions will not be used in the early stage of negotiations.
                    Rather, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1">Vance</persName> will contact the
                    Soviets informally, suggesting—as a first step—that the <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >US</gloss> and the Soviets negotiate an agreement that defines an attack on
                    a satellite of the other side as a hostile act. Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_VCR_1">Vance</persName> will also suggest that, as an indication
                    of good faith, both sides should immediately forego further <gloss
                        target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss> testing in space or against space objects.
                    Appropriate Congressional leaders are to be briefed on the <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> initiative, but the initial approach to the
                    Soviets will be informal, unpublicized and low-key, pending indications that
                    these negotiations have reasonable prospects for success.</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Relative Impact of a Treaty on Both Sides</p>
                <p>The Interagency Working Group (<gloss target="#t_IAWG_1">IAWG</gloss>) is tasked
                    to prepare a study of whether it would be more advantageous to negotiate a
                    Treaty that would accept the current US/Soviet <gloss target="#t_ASAT_1"
                        >ASAT</gloss> asymmetry in favor of the Soviets, or let the <gloss
                        target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss> testing continue on both sides until
                    capabilities on both sides have become more symmetrical.</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Verification</p>
                <p>Recognizing the difficulties in verifying an <gloss target="#t_ASAT_1"
                        >ASAT</gloss> Treaty using current national means, the <gloss
                        target="#t_IAWG_1">IAWG</gloss> is tasked to study whether the <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> should devise new systems and procedures
                    allowing improved verification. Included in the study will be an examination of
                    various satellite survivability techniques that the <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >US</gloss> might employ to improve verification of any <gloss
                        target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss> Treaty provision that prohibits hostile
                    actions against the other side’s satellites.</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">
                    <persName corresp="#p_PF_1">Press</persName> Releases/Public Statements</p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_IAWG_1">IAWG</gloss> will clear all press and public
                    statements concerning <gloss target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss> negotiations,
                    capabilities and other activities.</p>
                <pb facs="0075" n="44" xml:id="pg_44"/>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Forum for Future Negotiations</p>
                <p>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName>, Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_VCR_1">Vance</persName> and Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_BH_1">Brown</persName> will decide later, among themselves, what
                    forum the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> will propose for conducting <gloss
                        target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss> Treaty negotiations.</p>
            </div>
